Fig. 8
a and b displays the effect of C (pH) and D (irradiation time) factors on MB removal with constant catalyst loading of 1.5 g/L and dye concentration of 35 ppm. Both plots indicated the ascending trend of irradiation time on the response. Furthermore, increasing the alkalinity of the solution (from pH of 5–11) resulted in a 19% improvement in removal efficiency (79–98%). This trend is justified by the fact that MB is a cationic dye which has a positively charged sulfite functional group. The catalyst surface is negatively charged at pH values higher than the particular point of zero charge (pHPZC), and positively charged at pH < pHPZC [58]. MIL-53 (Fe) and 3-NCM (Fe) were found to have pHPZC values of 7.3 and 8.4, respectively (Fig. 9
). As a result, while being negatively charged at basic pH, the 3-NCM (Fe) surface electrostatically attracted the MB molecules, leading to substantial MB adsorption on its surface.
